Unique TensorFlower"},"message":"Predicate in constraint should suppose the arg will be the base type instead of the derived type

For example,
def TrueBoolAttr : AttrConstraint<CPred<"$_self.getValue()">>;
It supposes "$_self" will be the derived attribute "BoolAttr". But in fact, it depends on the implementation of ODS and DRR tblgen backends. We should suppose it'll be the base type "Attribute" and do the casting inside the expression.

Please also check the discussion here, https://llvm.discourse.group/t/self-will-be-the-base-type-of-the-entity-that-attaches-to-a-predicate/4367/5 and the description in mlir, https://github.com/llvm/llvm-project/commit/2fa22488d5d11e2b3f7cefc3bd19f73c27fc6dac#diff-31fca2ded8444f4b01301b4d29993255513393c6fecf6f5f07188d7aa0d3f66a

Unique TensorFlower"},"message":"Predicate in constraint should suppose the arg will be the base type instead of the derived type

For example,
def TrueBoolAttr : AttrConstraint<CPred<"$_self.getValue()">>;
It supposes "$_self" will be the derived attribute "BoolAttr". But in fact, it depends on the implementation of ODS and DRR tblgen backends. We should suppose it'll be the base type "Attribute" and do the casting inside the expression.

Please also check the discussion here, https://llvm.discourse.group/t/self-will-be-the-base-type-of-the-entity-that-attaches-to-a-predicate/4367/5 and the description in mlir, https://github.com/llvm/llvm-project/commit/2fa22488d5d11e2b3f7cefc3bd19f73c27fc6dac#diff-31fca2ded8444f4b01301b4d29993255513393c6fecf6f5f07188d7aa0d3f66a

[{"sha":"3c87469de7d3a5befff09ea3f4140f6f76fe82f0","author":{"email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org","name":"A. Unique TensorFlower"},"message":"Predicate in constraint should suppose the arg will be the base type instead of the derived type

For example,
def TrueBoolAttr : AttrConstraint<CPred<"$_self.getValue()">>;
It supposes "$_self" will be the derived attribute "BoolAttr". But in fact, it depends on the implementation of ODS and DRR tblgen backends. We should suppose it'll be the base type "Attribute" and do the casting inside the expression.

Please also check the discussion here, https://llvm.discourse.group/t/self-will-be-the-base-type-of-the-entity-that-attaches-to-a-predicate/4367/5 and the description in mlir, https://github.com/llvm/llvm-project/commit/2fa22488d5d11e2b3f7cefc3bd19f73c27fc6dac#diff-31fca2ded8444f4b01301b4d29993255513393c6fecf6f5f07188d7aa0d3f66a

[{"sha":"24a2bd630121cc3fd4dea49d79a63e70eb2de47b","author":{"email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com","name":"James Bardin"},"message":"tfproto version 6.1

Minor version increase to deprecate min_items and max_items in nested
types.

Nested types have MinItems and MaxItems fields that were inherited from
the block implementation, but were never validated by Terraform, and are
not supported by the HCL decoder validations. Mark these fields as
deprecated, indicating that the SDK should handle the required

MinItems and MaxItems are not used on nested types in the protocol, so

The init command needs to initialize a backend, in order to access
state, in turn to derive provider requirements from state. The backend
initialization step requires building provider factories, which
previously would fail if a lockfile was present without a corresponding
local provider cache.

This commit ensures that in this situation only, errors with the
provider factories are temporarily ignored. This allows us to continue
to initialize the backend, fetch providers, and then report any errors
as necessary.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/39de3ebec71e51d5eb44923129b67be732f5d6d8"},{"sha":"172943152049d94532a0707535ffbe7640414679","author":{"email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com","name":"Alisdair McDiarmid"},"message":"backend/remote: Fix version check when migrating

When migrating state to an existing Terraform Cloud workspace using the
remote backend, we check the remote version is compatible with the local
one by default.

This commit fixes two bugs in this code:

- If using the "name" strategy for the remote backend, the list of
  destination workspaces is empty. This resulted in no version checking
  of the remote workspace, and we fell back to the string equality
  check.
- The user-specified CLI flag `-ignore-remote-version` was not being
  applied for the state migration version checking.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/172943152049d94532a0707535ffbe7640414679"},{"sha":"92a9aa9b392985dc063ed586d3ff3f7b9787eb4a","author":{"email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com","name":"Alisdair McDiarmid"},"message":"Merge pull request #29792 from hashicorp/alisdair/init-missing-cache

When an explicit backend is configured with a configuration which has
not yet been initialized, running `terraform init` performs a state
migration to fetch the remotely stored state in order to operate on it.
Like the previous bug introduced by the recent provider diagnostics
change, this code path was not correctly configured to enable init mode
for the backend, which resulted in a fatal error during init when the
cache dir is deleted.

Setting the `Init` backend option allows this code path to continue
without error when first initializing the backend for state migration.
The new e2e test fails without this change.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/d42d83572b6362b934ab2850e783474671b7d2a0"},{"sha":"22923f987342b905acc989ac99a804f9a41334a4","author":{"email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com","name":"Alisdair McDiarmid"},"message":"Merge pull request #29793 from hashicorp/alisdair/fix-remote-backend-migrate-version-check

[{"sha":"7ab85d49e449be6fc3786f2624032464c21e72c1","author":{"email":"debc5fc5255503ceceb6184687cd26898e40e8ac@google.com","name":"Daniel Ellis"},"message":"Remove Loader._setup_functions_structures and move logic

Loader does too much.  This commit moves the setup of function structures to
the same place where concrete functions and their graphs and initialized.
This should improve cohesiveness and make the setup of concrete functions
and function graphs easier to follow.

This now uses the public interface for setting up these structures on
concrete functions' function graphs, rather than digging into private fields.

Ideally (probably), we should pass protos across the boundary and have the
objects themselves decide what their serialized state should look like.
Unfortunately, that will require moving `nested_structure_coder's usage into
function.py, which causes circular import issues.  That needs to be resolved
before we can do this.

[{"sha":"7ab85d49e449be6fc3786f2624032464c21e72c1","author":{"email":"debc5fc5255503ceceb6184687cd26898e40e8ac@google.com","name":"Daniel Ellis"},"message":"Remove Loader._setup_functions_structures and move logic

Loader does too much.  This commit moves the setup of function structures to
the same place where concrete functions and their graphs and initialized.
This should improve cohesiveness and make the setup of concrete functions
and function graphs easier to follow.

This now uses the public interface for setting up these structures on
concrete functions' function graphs, rather than digging into private fields.

Ideally (probably), we should pass protos across the boundary and have the
objects themselves decide what their serialized state should look like.
Unfortunately, that will require moving `nested_structure_coder's usage into
function.py, which causes circular import issues.  That needs to be resolved
before we can do this.
